body: "pm restore <id> <target> can rewrite an item back to a prior version, but there is no READ-ONLY way to inspect what an item looked like at a given version or timestamp. Agents auditing provenance today must either run a mutating restore (then restore back) or manually fold JSON Patch entries from pm history --full — expensive, error-prone, and impossible to compose in pipelines.\n\nProposal: a non-mutating projection flag on the read path:\n- pm get <id> --at <version|ISO timestamp> reconstructs the item state by replaying the append-only history stream up to the target and renders it through the normal get projection (json/toon, --tree excluded).\n- Output marks the projection clearly (as_of_version, as_of_timestamp, reconstructed: true) so downstream tooling can never confuse a historical view with current state.\n- Reuses the same replay engine as pm restore (shared SDK primitive; no second replay implementation) so restore and read-projection can never diverge.\n- SDK: expose as a first-class read primitive (getItemAt) so custom tools built on the SDK get time-travel reads for free — a prerequisite for building VCS-like systems on pm primitives.\n\nThis closes the read half of the durability story: the append-only hash-chained history already guarantees every version is recorded; this makes every version cheaply inspectable."
